<subSubSection pageId="111" pageNumber="112" type="names">
<paragraph pageId="111" pageNumber="112">Names.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="111" pageNumber="112">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">Myanmar</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">myat-y</emphasis>
a, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">mya-yar</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">myin-kahpan</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">ye-mya-yar</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">English</emphasis>
: microcos.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="111" pageNumber="112" type="range">
<paragraph pageId="111" pageNumber="112">Range.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="111" pageNumber="112">China, Cambodia, India, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, Sri Lanka, Thailand, and Vietnam. In Myanmar, found in Ayeyarwady, Bago, Mandalay, Mon, Taninthayi, and Yangon.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="111" pageNumber="112" type="uses">
<paragraph pageId="111" pageNumber="112">Uses.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="111" pageNumber="112">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">Whole plant</emphasis>
: Used for skin diseases and indigestion.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="111" pageNumber="112" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="111" pageNumber="112">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="111" pageNumber="112">
In India the whole plant is used for syphilitic ulcers and eczema, and the leaf is narcotic (
